<highlight>
<T1>internet scam artists are exploiting superstorm sandy by creating fraudulent donation websites.</T1>

<T1.1>thousands of sandy-related domain names were registered around the time of the storm.</T1.1>
<T1.1.1>more than 1,000 domains containing the words "sandy" or "relief" were registered as the storm approached.</T1.1.1>
<T1.1.2>some domains were registered even before the hurricane made landfall.</T1.1.2>
<T1.1.3>many such domains are registered as soon as the national weather service announces hurricane names each spring.</T1.1.3>

<T1.2>the purpose of these websites varies widely, with some being legitimate and others fraudulent.</T1.2>
<T1.2.1>some sites were created by construction companies, lawyers, or repair firms seeking business opportunities.</T1.2.1>
<T1.2.2>other sites are more questionable and appear designed to trick people into donating money.</T1.2.2>
<T1.2.2.1>one jamaica-related relief site linked donors to a paypal account registered to an individual in north carolina.</T1.2.2.1>
<T1.2.2.2>the charity was not registered with the north carolina secretary of state as required by law.</T1.2.2.2>

<T1.3>crowdfunding platforms are also hosting numerous appeals from sandy victims.</T1.3>
<T1.3.1>indiegogo has more than 32 pages of pleas for cash donations from those affected by the storm.</T1.3.1>
<T1.3.2>it is difficult to verify the authenticity of individual appeals on such platforms.</T1.3.2>

<T1.4>authorities and watchdog groups are warning the public about donation scams.</T1.4>
<T1.4.1>the fbi issued a public warning urging donors to apply a critical eye before giving.</T1.4.1>
<T1.4.2>the better business bureau's wise giving alliance expressed concern that things will get worse.</T1.4.2>
<T1.4.2.1>according to the bbb, 70% of americans donate without checking where their money goes.</T1.4.2.1>
<T1.4.2.2>people will continue to be duped by unscrupulous claims.</T1.4.2.2>

<T1.5>legitimate charitable organizations are continuing their relief efforts.</T1.5>
<T1.5.1>convoy of hope distributed supplies in new jersey, acknowledging that some organizations operate for the wrong reasons.</T1.5.1>
<T1.5.2>the american red cross has raised $103 million specifically earmarked for sandy victims.</T1.5.2>
